40|$|In this book, terrorism, sabotage, and {{subversion}} {{are analyzed}} {{to challenge the}} dominant views that a ‘new conflict’ is now posing unprecedented threats to U. S. homeland security. Since 9 / 11, the dominant view {{is that we have}} entered an era of ‘new conflict’ in which technology has empowered non-state actors who now pose unprecedented and unmanageable threats to U. S. national security. From <b>homegrown</b> and foreign <b>terrorism</b> to the possibility of cyber sabotage and fears of religious subversion, David Tucker challenges every aspect of this ‘new conflict’ argument, writes Maria Kuecken...|$|R
40|$|The {{last decade}} marked a {{significant}} change in the European Union‟s approach towards terrorism. As a result of terrorist attacks (9 / 11, Madrid and London) the EU terrorism policy turned from a counter-terrorism approach, stressing repressive efforts targeting an outside threat, towards a counter-radicalization approach, targeting domestic radicalization processes. Led by the Netherlands and the United Kingdom, the latter approach based itself on a <b>homegrown</b> dimension of <b>terrorism</b> in which identification and resolving underlying causes of radicalization took center stage (Coolsaet 2012, 868). This shift was quite a significant one, since it influenced the traditional sovereignty of member states to deal with these issues themselves (Coolsaet 2012, 689). Genomineerd voor de Van den Berg Bachelorscriptieprijs...|$|R
40|$|The {{purpose of}} this study is to {{investigate}} whether India’s democratic [...] institutions have effectively included Muslims as citizens fully capable of pursuing [...] their interests through peaceful means; or have, by excluding Muslims, contributed to a [...] rise in terrorist activity by external and internal Islamic extremist organizations in a [...] period of time when Islamic terrorism has grown worldwide. Has radical Islam as [...] global phenomena had a measurable effect on the formation of groups with an extremist [...] agenda in India? Has the rise to power of radical Hindu parties^in India’s national [...] parliament and state governments, contributed to a rise in violence? Has the Indian [...] government responded positively to recommendations by experts to prevent terrorism [...] by enacting and implementing legislation that prevents Muslims from turning to [...] terrorist alternatives? This study primarily uses qualitative means to answer these [...] questions. However, empirical analysis is used to supplement qualitative case studies [...] by introducing evidence of the opinions of Muslims towards India’s democratic [...] institutions. The study concludes that there has been an increase in <b>homegrown</b> [...] <b>terrorism</b> because India has not only failed to provide equal access to its institutions for [...] Muslims, but has even worked against them at time^hus^contributing to an increase in [...] terrorist activity...|$|R
